actionability.title: Auto-waiting
actionability.description: Playwright performs a range of actionability checks on the elements before making actions to ensure these actions behave as expected. It auto-waits for all the relevant checks to pass and only then performs the requested action. If the required checks do not pass within the given timeout, action fails with the TimeoutError.

api/class-accessibility.title: Accessibility
api/class-accessibility.description: The Accessibility class provides methods for inspecting Chromium's accessibility tree. The accessibility tree is used by assistive technology such as screen readers or switches.

api/class-browsertype.title: BrowserType
api/class-browsertype.description: BrowserType provides methods to launch a specific browser instance or connect to an existing one. The following is a typical example of using Playwright to drive automation:

api/class-consolemessage.title: ConsoleMessage
api/class-consolemessage.description: ConsoleMessage] objects are dispatched by page via the [event Page.Console event. For each console messages logged in the page there will be corresponding event in the Playwright context.

api/class-dialog.title: Dialog
api/class-dialog.description: Dialog] objects are dispatched by page via the [event Page.Dialog event.

api/class-download.title: Download
api/class-download.description: Download] objects are dispatched by page via the [event Page.Download event.

api/class-filechooser.title: FileChooser
api/class-filechooser.description: FileChooser] objects are dispatched by the page in the [event Page.FileChooser event.

api/class-frame.title: Frame
api/class-frame.description: At every point of time, page exposes its current frame tree via the Page.MainFrame and Frame.ChildFrames methods.

api/class-framelocator.title: FrameLocator
api/class-framelocator.description: FrameLocator represents a view to the iframe on the page. It captures the logic sufficient to retrieve the iframe and locate elements in that iframe. FrameLocator can be created with either Page.FrameLocator(selector) or Locator.FrameLocator(selector) method.

api/class-jshandle.title: JSHandle
api/class-jshandle.description: JSHandle represents an in-page JavaScript object. JSHandles can be created with the Page.EvaluateHandleAsync(expression, arg) method.

api/class-keyboard.title: Keyboard
api/class-keyboard.description: Keyboard provides an api for managing a virtual keyboard. The high level api is Keyboard.TypeAsync(text, options), which takes raw characters and generates proper keydown, keypress/input, and keyup events on your page.

api/class-locator.title: Locator
api/class-locator.description: Locators are the central piece of Playwright's auto-waiting and retry-ability. In a nutshell, locators represent a way to find element(s) on the page at any moment. Locator can be created with the Page.Locator(selector, options) method.

api/class-mouse.title: Mouse
api/class-mouse.description: The Mouse class operates in main-frame CSS pixels relative to the top-left corner of the viewport.

api/class-playwright.title: Playwright
api/class-playwright.description: Playwright module provides a method to launch a browser instance. The following is a typical example of using Playwright to drive automation:

api/class-request.title: Request
api/class-request.description: Whenever the page sends a request for a network resource the following sequence of events are emitted by [Page]:

api/class-response.title: Response
api/class-response.description: [Response] class represents responses which are received by page.

api/class-route.title: Route
api/class-route.description: Whenever a network route is set up with Page.RouteAsync(url, handler, options) or BrowserContext.RouteAsync(url, handler, options), the Route object allows to handle the route.

api/class-selectors.title: Selectors
api/class-selectors.description: Selectors can be used to install custom selector engines. See Working with selectors for more information.

api/class-touchscreen.title: Touchscreen
api/class-touchscreen.description: The Touchscreen class operates in main-frame CSS pixels relative to the top-left corner of the viewport. Methods on the touchscreen can only be used in browser contexts that have been initialized with hasTouch set to true.

api/class-tracing.title: Tracing
api/class-tracing.description: API for collecting and saving Playwright traces. Playwright traces can be opened in Trace Viewer after Playwright script runs.

api/class-video.title: Video
api/class-video.description: When browser context is created with the recordVideo option, each page has a video object associated with it.

api/class-websocket.title: WebSocket
api/class-websocket.description: The [WebSocket] class represents websocket connections in the page.

api/class-websocketframe.title: WebSocketFrame
api/class-websocketframe.description: The WebSocketFrame] class represents frames sent over [WebSocket] connections in the page. Frame payload is returned by either [WebSocketFrame.Text or WebSocketFrame.Binary method depending on the its type.

api/class-worker.title: Worker
api/class-worker.description: The Worker class represents a WebWorker. worker event is emitted on the page object to signal a worker creation. close event is emitted on the worker object when the worker is gone.

auth.title: Authentication
auth.description: Playwright can be used to automate scenarios that require authentication.

browsers.title: Browsers
browsers.description: Each version of Playwright needs specific versions of browser binaries to operate. Depending on the language you use, Playwright will either download these browsers at package install time for you, or you will need to use Playwright CLI to install these browsers.

ci.title: Continuous Integration
ci.description: Playwright tests can be executed in CI environments. We have created sample configurations for common CI providers.

cli.title: Command line tools
cli.description: Playwright comes with the command line tools.

codegen.title: Test Generator
codegen.description: Playwright comes with the ability to generate tests out of the box.

debug.title: Debugging tools
debug.description: Playwright scripts work with existing debugging tools, like Node.js debuggers and browser developer tools. Playwright also introduces new debugging features for browser automation.

dialogs.title: Dialogs
dialogs.description: Playwright can interact with the web page dialogs such as alert, confirm, prompt as well as beforeunload confirmation.

docker.title: Docker
docker.description: [Dockerfile.focal] can be used to run Playwright scripts in Docker environment. These image includes all the dependencies needed to run browsers in a Docker container, and also include the browsers themselves.

downloads.title: Downloads
downloads.description: For uploading files, see the uploading files section.

emulation.title: Emulation
emulation.description: Playwright allows overriding various parameters of the device where the browser is running:

evaluating.title: Evaluating JavaScript
evaluating.description: Playwright scripts run in your Playwright environment. Your page scripts run in the browser page environment. Those environments don't intersect, they are running in different virtual machines in different processes and even potentially on different computers.

events.title: Events
events.description: Playwright allows listening to various types of events happening in the web page, such as network requests, creation of child pages, dedicated workers etc. There are several ways to subscribe to such events:

handles.title: Handles
handles.description: Playwright can create handles to the page DOM elements or any other objects inside the page. These handles live in the Playwright process, whereas the actual objects live in the browser. There are two types of handles:

inspector.title: Inspector
inspector.description: Playwright Inspector is a GUI tool that helps authoring and debugging Playwright scripts.

languages.title: Supported languages
languages.description: The Playwright API is available in multiple languages.

locators.title: Locators
locators.description: Locator]s are the central piece of Playwright's auto-waiting and retry-ability. In a nutshell, locators represent a way to find element(s) on the page at any moment. Locator can be created with the [Page.Locator(selector, options) method.

navigations.title: Navigations
navigations.description: Playwright can navigate to URLs and handle navigations caused by page interactions. This guide covers common scenarios to wait for page navigations and loading to complete.

network.title: Network
network.description: Playwright provides APIs to monitor and modify network traffic, both HTTP and HTTPS. Any requests that page does, including XHRs and fetch requests, can be tracked, modified and handled.

pom.title: Page Object Models
pom.description: Large test suites can be structured to optimize ease of authoring and maintenance. Page object models are one such approach to structure your test suite.

screenshots.title: Screenshots
screenshots.description: Here is a quick way to capture a screenshot and save it into a file:

selectors.title: Selectors
selectors.description: Selectors are strings that are used to create Locator]s. Locators are used to perform actions on the elements by means of methods such as [Locator.ClickAsync(options), Locator.FillAsync(value, options) and alike.

test-assertions.title: Assertions
test-assertions.description: Playwright gives you Web-First Assertions with convenience methods for creating assertions that will wait and retry until the expected condition is met.

test-runners.title: Test Runners
test-runners.description: While Playwright for .NET isn't tied to a particular test runner or testing framework, in our experience it works best with the built-in .NET test runner, and using NUnit as the test framework. NUnit is also what we use internally for our tests.

trace-viewer.title: Trace Viewer
trace-viewer.description: Playwright Trace Viewer is a GUI tool that helps exploring recorded Playwright traces after the script ran. Open traces locally or in your browser on trace.playwright.dev.

videos.title: Videos
videos.description: Playwright can record videos for all pages in a browser context. Videos are saved upon context closure, so make sure to await BrowserContext.CloseAsync().

why-playwright.title: Why Playwright?
why-playwright.description: Playwright enables fast, reliable and capable testing and automation across all modern browsers. This guide covers those key differentiators to help you decide on the right tool for your automated tests.
